t%2C%20given%20that%20a%20lot%20of%20it%20goes%20unused.%C2%A0%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EOne%20in%20three%20retirees%20increase%20their%20wealth%2C%20and%20most%20curb%20their%20spending%20naturally%2C%20he%20explains.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.diewithzerobook.com%2Fwelcome%5C%22%3EAuthor%20Bill%20Perkins%3C%2Fa%3E%20hopes%20to%20run%20out%20of%20money%20in%20retirement.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20he%20has%20saved%20for%20retirement%2C%20and%20he%20does%20hope%20to%20use%20that%20money%2C%20he%20hopes%20to%20%3Cem%3Ereally%3C%2Fem%3E%20use%20it%20%E2%80%94%20he%20wants%20to%20spend%20his%20balance%20down%20to%20nothing.%20Instead%20of%20leaving%20a%20large%20inheritance%2C%20he'd%20rather%20use%20his%20money%20on%20experiences%2C%20helping%20his%20children%20while%20they're%20starting%20out%2C%20and%20spending%20the%20money%20on%20his%20needs.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20it%20goes%20against%20traditional%20retirement%20planning%20logic%2C%20Perkins%20says%20that%20people%20may%20be%20saving%20too%20much%20for%20retirement%2C%20holding%20them%20back%20from%20living%20and%20having%20meaningful%20experiences%20while%20they're%20able.%20While%20that%20comes%20at%20the%20expense%20of%20saving%20more%20for%20later%2C%20that%20might%20not%20be%20a%20bad%20thing.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20his%202020%20book%20%26quot%3B%3Cspan%3EDie%20with%20Zero%3C%2Fspan%3E%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20explains%20that%20there%20are%20four%20big%20reasons%20many%20people%20could%20actually%20be%20OK%20saving%20a%20bit%20less%20than%20they%20originally%20thought%20they'd%20need.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E1.%20Net%20worth%20tends%20to%20increase%20in%20retirement%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fwhat-is-net-worth%5C%22%3ENet%20worth%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20or%20a%20total%20of%20all%20of%20your%20assets%20minus%20any%20loans%20or%20debt%2C%20tends%20to%20increase%20with%20age.%20And%2C%20that%20includes%20into%20retirement%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPerkins%20writes%20that%20about%20a%20third%20of%20retirees%20actually%20see%20their%20net%20worth%20increase%20in%20retirement.%20According%20to%202016%20Federal%20Reserve%20Board%20data%2C%20median%20and%20average%20net%20worth%20for%20people%20over%20the%20age%20of%2075%20was%20higher%20than%20that%20of%20those%2065-%20to%2074-year-olds%2C%20also%20presumably%20past%20retirement%20age.%C2%A0The%20median%20net%20worth%20for%20those%20over%20age%2075%20was%20%24281%2C600%2C%20compared%20to%20%24237%2C600%20for%20those%20between%2065%20and%2074.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20some%20people%20did%20use%20up%20their%20money%2C%20many%20retirees%20actually%20see%20their%20net%20worth%20increase%20with%20time.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E2.%20Healthcare%20costs%20are%20high%2C%20but%20no%20amount%20of%20money%20can%20cover%20the%20worst-case%20scenarios%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EHealthcare%20costs%20are%20a%20major%20expense%20in%20retirement%20and%2C%20for%20many%2C%20a%20big%20surprise%20when%20it%20comes%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fbest-retirement-plans%5C%22%3Eretirement%20plan%3C%2Fa%3E%20savings.%20But%C2%A0Perkins%20says%20it's%20not%20worth%20worrying%20about.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BTo%20put%20it%20bluntly%2C%20no%20amount%20of%20savings%20available%20to%20most%20people%20will%20cover%20the%20costliest%20healthcare%20you%20might%20possibly%20need%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20writes.%20He%20cites%20million-dollar%20cancer%20treatments%20and%20his%20father's%20%2450%2C000-per-night%20hospital%20stay%20as%20examples.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20Medicare%20and%20its%20supplements%20can%20make%20healthcare%20more%20affordable%2C%20there's%20no%20way%20to%20save%20for%20the%20worst%20possible%20scenarios.%20%26quot%3BUninsured%20medical%20care%20is%20so%20expensive%2C%20it%20won't%20make%20any%20real%20difference%20for%20the%20vast%20majority%20of%20us%20whether%20we%20save%20for%20it%20or%20not%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20writes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EUltimately%2C%20Perkins%20feels%20this%20money%20is%20better%20spent%20when%20you're%20younger.%20%26quot%3BIt%20is%20much%20smarter%20to%20spend%20your%20healthcare%20money%20on%20the%20front%20end%20(to%20maintain%20your%20health%20and%20try%20to%20prevent%20disease)%20than%20to%20spend%20it%20at%20the%20end%2C%20when%20you%20get%20a%20lot%20less%20bang%20for%20every%20buck%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20writes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E3.%20It's%20easier%20than%20you%20think%20to%20decrease%20your%20expenses%20later%20on%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EMany%20people%20tend%20to%20decrease%20their%20spending%20naturally%20as%20their%20expenses%20go%20down%20in%20retirement%2C%20and%20overspending%20doesn't%20seem%20to%20be%20an%20issue%20for%20many%20retirees.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20median%20ratio%20of%20household%20spending%20to%20household%20income%20hovers%20around%201%3A1.%20This%20means%20that%20people's%20spending%20continues%20to%20closely%20track%20their%20income%2C%26quot%3B%20writes%20Perkins.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EDespite%20the%20fact%20that%20some%20items%20do%20get%20more%20expensive%20%E2%80%94%20take%20healthcare%20as%20an%20example%20%E2%80%94%20other%20things%20get%20cheaper.%20Perkins%20cites%202017%20Consumer%20Expenditure%20survey%20data%2C%20where%20average%20spending%20for%20households%20aged%2055%20to%2064%20spent%20%2464%2C000%2C%2065-%20to%2074-year-olds%20spent%20%2455%2C000%2C%20and%20those%2075%20and%20older%20spent%20%2442%2C000.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThis%20overall%20decline%20occurred%20despite%20a%20rise%20in%20healthcare%20expenses%2C%20because%20most%20other%20expenses%2C%20such%20as%20clothing%20and%20entertainment%2C%20were%20much%20lower%2C%26quot%3B%20Perkins%20writes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E4.%20Most%20people%20only%20spend%20a%20portion%20of%20what%20they%20have%20saved%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EPerkins'%20book%20repeats%20the%20fact%20that%20most%20people%20only%20touch%20a%20portion%20of%20what%20they%20have%20saved.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETo%20prove%20this%2C%20Perkins%20collected%20data%20from%20a%20range%20of%20retirement%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fbest-budgeting-apps%5C%22%3Ebudgets%3C%2Fa%3E.%20%26quot%3BRetirees%20who%20had%20%24500%2C000%20or%20more%20right%20before%20retirement%20had%20spent%20down%20a%20median%20of%20only%2011.5%25%20of%20that%20money%2020%20years%20later%20or%20by%20the%20time%20they%20died%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20writes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnd%2C%20this%20pattern%20held%20true%20even%20for%20those%20with%20smaller%20savings.%20%26quot%3BRetirees%20with%20less%20than%20%24200%2C000%20saved%20up%20for%20retirement%20...%20had%20spent%20down%20only%20one%20quarter%20of%20their%20assets%2018%20years%20after%20retirement.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20saving%20too%20much%20isn't%20inherently%20bad%2C%20it%20could%20be%20if%20it%20prevents%20you%20from%20doing%20the%20things%20you%20want%20to%20do%20while%20you're%20still%20able.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Caside%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fsmartasset.com%2Fretirement%2Ffind-a-financial-planner%3Futm_source%3Dbusinessinsider%26utm_medium%3Dcpc%26utm_campaign%3Dbus__falc_bicontent%26utm_content%3DBI%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EFinding%20a%20financial%20advisor%3C%2Fa%3E%20doesn't%20have%20to%20be%20hard.%20SmartAsset's%20free%20tool%20matches%20you%20with%20up%20to%20three%20fiduciary%20financial%20advisors%20that%20serve%20your%20area%20in%20minutes.%20Each%20advisor%20has%20been%20vetted%20by%20SmartAsset%20and%20is%20held%20to%20a%20fiduciary%20standard%20to%20act%20in%20your%20best%20interests.%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fsmartasset.com%2Fretirement%2Ffind-a-financial-planner%3Futm_source%3Dbusinessinsider%26utm_medium%3Dcpc%26utm_campaign%3Dbus__falc_bicontent%26utm_content%3DBI%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%20Start%20your%20search%20now.%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Faside%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThis%20article%20was%20original